---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro"
import { getCollection } from "astro:content"

let topics = []
try {
  topics = await getCollection("topics")
} catch {}

const principles = (await getCollection("principles")).sort((a, b) => a.data.number - b.data.number)
const structural = principles.filter((p) => p.data.tier === "structural")
const substantive = principles.filter((p) => p.data.tier === "substantive")
---

<BaseLayout>
  <!-- Hero -->
  <section class="hero-section relative overflow-hidden">
    <div class="container max-w-4xl relative py-20 lg:py-28">
      <!-- Masthead -->
      <div class="flex items-start gap-5 md:gap-8 mb-10">
        <img
          src="/favicon.svg"
          alt=""
          class="hero-logo w-20 h-20 md:w-28 md:h-28 lg:w-32 lg:h-32 shrink-0"
        />
        <div>
          <h1 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl lg:text-5xl font-bold font-heading tracking-tight">
            Redemocratize
          </h1>
          <p class="text-base md:text-lg lg:text-xl italic text-base-content/70 mt-2 leading-snug">
            Design Principles for Democratic Self-Governance
          </p>
          <p
            class="text-base md:text-lg lg:text-xl italic text-base-content/70 mt-0.5 leading-snug"
          >
            Laboratory for Collaborative Democracy
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Rule -->
      <div class="hero-rule h-px mb-8 md:mb-12"></div>

      <!-- Manifesto -->
      <div class="text-base md:text-xl space-y-3 text-base-content/85">
        <p>
          Democratic governance is under assault everywhere, but
          <em>democracy</em> is not the problem.
        </p>
        <p>The problem is institutional vulnerability to capture.</p>
        <p>We know what's breaking. The harder question is: how do we rebuild?</p>
        <p>Constitutions designed to resist change cannot resist capture.</p>
        <p>Redemocratize offers resilient principles for the world we actually inhabit.</p>
        <p class="font-semibold text-base-content">
          The answer to capture is not resistance. It's better design.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- The Problem -->
  <section class="py-20 lg:py-24 bg-base-200">
    <div class="container max-w-4xl">
      <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold font-heading mb-8">The Problem</h2>
      <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
        <p>
          The crisis is not one failure. It is an accumulation, with each structural breakdown
          creating the conditions for the next, built on a founding design that would never be able
          to correct itself.
        </p>
        <p>
          The Constitution's amendment process was made deliberately difficult to satisfy, designed
          to protect the structural advantages of the states that demanded it. The concentrated
          wealth that now dominates American politics did not subvert a healthy democracy. It moved
          into a structure the framers left unguarded, and used the tools of democratic governance
          to ensure it could not be dislodged.
        </p>
        <p>
          These failures are neither accident nor conspiracy. They are the predictable result of
          constitutional designs that assumed good faith, relied on norms instead of structure, and
          provided no realistic mechanism for their own renewal.
        </p>
        <p>
          The 21st century has compounded the crisis with threats no 18th-century framework could
          have anticipated: industrialized manipulation of the information environment, AI-generated
          disinformation at scale, corporate-authoritarian alignment, automated surveillance, the
          enclosure of shared wealth by a shrinking oligarchic class, and ecological breakdown that
          the existing system has no structural capacity to address.
        </p>
        <p>
          We no longer live in the eighteenth century, but we are governed by an eighteenth-century
          social contract that no living person chose or consented to. The present moment does not
          demand that we abandon democracy. It demands that we build democratic institutions robust
          to the world we actually inhabit.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="mt-12">
        <a href="/lab/articles/cumulative-crises" class="btn btn-outline btn-primary font-heading">
          Read more ...
        </a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Our Approach -->
  <section class="py-20 lg:py-24">
    <div class="container max-w-4xl">
      <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold font-heading mb-8">Our Approach</h2>
      <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
        <p>Redemocratize articulates capture-resistant design principles for modern democracy.</p>
        <p>
          The framework addresses problems that existing constitutions were not designed for:
          algorithmic manipulation of public discourse, the concentration of epistemic power in
          unaccountable private hands, automated systems making decisions about human rights, extreme
          wealth that negates democratic self-governance, ecological limits that no political
          arrangement can override, and institutional capture by actors who use the tools of
          democracy to dismantle it.
        </p>
        <p>
          The principles function as architectural elements around which resilient government
          institutions may be constructed. We evaluate institutional forms by how well they serve
          the principles, not by how closely they resemble what exists.
        </p>
        <p>
          We invite collaborators to apply these design principles to specific governance challenges
          and the creation of new democratic forms, and provide infrastructure and support for the
          work of building functional democracy.
        </p>
        <p>
          This is closer to an open-source software project than a political campaign. The
          principles are developed in the open. Contributions are encouraged. Everything is
          versioned, transparent, and revisable — because a project advocating for adaptive
          governance must first practice it.
        </p>
        <p>We are just getting started, but we are building in the open.</p>
        <p>
          You are invited to <a href="/contribute">join us</a> in ensuring that government of the people,
          by the people, for the people does not perish from the earth.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Fifteen Principles -->
  <section class="py-20 lg:py-28 bg-base-200">
    <div class="container max-w-5xl">
      <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold font-heading mb-10">The Redemocratize Principles</h2>

      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-12 lg:gap-16">
        <div>
          <h3 class="text-xl font-bold font-heading mb-6 text-primary">
            How governance is organized
          </h3>
          <dl class="space-y-6">
            {
              structural.map((p) => (
                <div>
                  <dt class="font-bold font-heading">
                    <a href={`/principles/${p.id}`} class="link link-hover">
                      {p.data.title}
                    </a>
                  </dt>
                  <dd class="text-base-content/80 mt-1">{p.data.summary}</dd>
                </div>
              ))
            }
          </dl>
        </div>

        <div>
          <h3 class="text-xl font-bold font-heading mb-6 text-accent">
            What governance must protect
          </h3>
          <dl class="space-y-6">
            {
              substantive.map((p) => (
                <div>
                  <dt class="font-bold font-heading">
                    <a href={`/principles/${p.id}`} class="link link-hover">
                      {p.data.title}
                    </a>
                  </dt>
                  <dd class="text-base-content/80 mt-1">{p.data.summary}</dd>
                </div>
              ))
            }
          </dl>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="mt-12">
        <a href="/principles" class="btn btn-primary font-heading">Explore the principles</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- What We Build On -->
  <section class="py-20 lg:py-24">
    <div class="container max-w-4xl">
      <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold font-heading mb-8">On the Shoulders of Giants</h2>
      <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
        <p>
          This project is not nihilistic about existing democratic traditions. Many principles
          embedded in those traditions are sound — due process, freedom of conscience, separation of
          powers, civilian control of the military, the rejection of hereditary privilege. The
          crisis is that institutional implementations have failed these principles.
        </p>
        <p>
          We claim these traditions more seriously than those defending the status quo. We insist on
          fulfilling what they promised but could not deliver.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="mt-10">
        <a
          href="/lab/articles/inherited-principles"
          class="btn btn-outline btn-primary font-heading"
        >
          Read about inherited principles
        </a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Start Here -->
  <section class="py-20 lg:py-24 bg-base-200">
    <div class="container max-w-4xl">
      <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold font-heading mb-8">The Principles Applied</h2>
      <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
        <p>
          The principles are the intellectual architecture. But most people think in terms of
          issues. These topic pages show how the principles apply to the things you care about.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="mt-10 space-y-5">
        <div class="card bg-base-100 shadow-sm">
          <div class="card-body p-5">
            <h3 class="card-title text-base font-heading">
              Preventing & Defeating Authoritarianism
            </h3>
            <p class="text-sm text-base-content/70">
              How the entire framework is designed to make authoritarian capture structurally
              impossible.
            </p>
            <div class="card-actions justify-end">
              <a href="/lab/topics/authoritarianism" class="btn btn-sm btn-primary font-heading">
                Read
              </a>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="card bg-base-100 shadow-sm">
          <div class="card-body p-5">
            <h3 class="card-title text-base font-heading">Wealth Inequality & Oligarchy</h3>
            <p class="text-sm text-base-content/70">
              Why extreme wealth concentration is inherently incompatible with democracy, and what
              governance designed to prevent it looks like.
            </p>
            <div class="card-actions justify-end">
              <a href="/lab/topics/wealth-inequality" class="btn btn-sm btn-primary font-heading">
                Read
              </a>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p class="mt-8 text-base-content/70">
        Help us develop: Education, Immigration, Healthcare, Criminal Justice,
        Climate & Environment, Labor & Work, Technology & Privacy, Money & Politics
      </p>

      <div class="mt-8">
        <a href="/lab" class="btn btn-outline btn-primary font-heading">Explore the Lab</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Contribute -->
  <section class="py-20 lg:py-24">
    <div class="container max-w-4xl">
      <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold font-heading mb-8">Contribute</h2>
      <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
        <p>
          This is an open project. The principles are developed in the open and contributions are
          welcome from anyone — scholars, organizers, lawyers, technologists, citizens.
        </p>
        <p>
          You can contribute essays and analysis on how the principles apply to issues you know. You
          can propose institutional mechanisms that serve the principles. You can bring comparative
          examples from other democratic traditions. You can translate.
        </p>
        <p>
          We use Google Docs for accessibility — you don't need to know git to participate. All
          content is licensed CC BY-SA.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="mt-10">
        <a href="/contribute" class="btn btn-primary font-heading">How to contribute</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Stay Connected -->
  <section class="py-20 lg:py-24">
    <div class="container max-w-4xl text-center">
      <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold font-heading mb-8">Stay Connected</h2>
      <p class="text-lg text-base-content/80 mb-10">
        Join the mailing list to follow the project's development and be notified of new content and
        opportunities to contribute.
      </p>
      <form id="subscribe-form" class="flex flex-col items-center gap-4">
        <div class="join">
          <input
            type="email"
            id="subscribe-email"
            placeholder="your@email.com"
            class="input join-item w-64"
            required
            pattern="[^@\s]+@[^@\s]+\.[^@\s]+"
            title="Please enter a valid email address"
          />
          <button type="submit" class="btn btn-primary join-item font-heading">
            Subscribe
          </button>
        </div>
        <div class="cf-turnstile" data-sitekey="0x4AAAAAACwW6ap8A70BtVeG" data-theme="auto"></div>
      </form>
      <p id="subscribe-message" class="mt-4 text-sm hidden"></p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <script src="https://challenges.cloudflare.com/turnstile/v0/api.js" async defer></script>

  <script>
    const form = document.getElementById("subscribe-form");
    const emailInput = document.getElementById("subscribe-email");
    const message = document.getElementById("subscribe-message");

    form.addEventListener("submit", async (e) => {
      e.preventDefault();
      const email = emailInput.value.trim();
      if (!email) return;

      const turnstileToken = form.querySelector("[name='cf-turnstile-response']")?.value;
      if (!turnstileToken) {
        message.textContent = "Please complete the verification.";
        message.className = "mt-4 text-sm text-error";
        return;
      }

      const button = form.querySelector("button");
      button.disabled = true;
      button.textContent = "Subscribing...";
      message.classList.add("hidden");

      try {
        const res = await fetch("/api/subscribe", {
          method: "POST",
          headers: { "Content-Type": "application/json" },
          body: JSON.stringify({ email, turnstileToken }),
        });

        const data = await res.json().catch(() => null);

        if (res.ok) {
          message.textContent =
            "Check your email to confirm your subscription.";
          message.className = "mt-4 text-sm text-success";
          emailInput.value = "";
          turnstile.reset();
        } else {
          message.textContent =
            data?.message || "Something went wrong. Please try again.";
          message.className = "mt-4 text-sm text-error";
        }
      } catch {
        message.textContent =
          "Could not reach the server. Please try again later.";
        message.className = "mt-4 text-sm text-error";
      } finally {
        button.disabled = false;
        button.textContent = "Subscribe";
      }
    });
  </script>
</BaseLayout>
